whereas.text:
Whereas democracy, human rights, and civil liberties are
			 universal values and fundamental principles of the foreign policy of the United
			 States;

Whereas the Supreme Leader of Iran is unelected, has the
			 power to veto any decision made by the president or parliament of Iran, and
			 controls the foreign and defense policy of Iran;

Whereas the current Supreme Leader of Iran has been in
			 power since 1989 and has never been subject to a popular referendum of any
			 kind;

paragraph.text:
recalls Senate
			 Resolution 386, 112th Congress, agreed to March 5, 2012, which called for free
			 and fair elections in Iran;

expresses support
			 for freedom, human rights, civil liberties, and rule of law in Iran, and for
			 elections that are free and fair;

condemns the
			 widespread human rights violations of the Government of the Islamic Republic of
			 Iran;

subparagraph.text:
holding elections
			 that are free, fair, and responsive to the people of Iran, including by
			 refraining from disqualifying candidates for political reasons;

making the
			 highest level of executive power in the Government of the Islamic Republic of
			 Iran accountable to the people of Iran through free and fair elections;

lifting
			 legislative restrictions on freedom of assembly, association, and expression;
			 and

allowing the
			 Internet to remain free and open and allowing domestic and international media
			 to operate freely;

paragraph.text:
calls on the
			 Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran to allow international election
			 monitors to be present for the June 14, 2013, election;

subparagraph.text:
to express
			 support for the universal rights and freedoms of the people of Iran, including
			 to democratic self-government and fully accountable elected leaders;
